    <text>
        <body>
        	<div1 type="letter">
        		<head>Jim to Mademoiselle Marcelle Guerin <date value="1916-12-15">Dec 15th [1916]</date></head>
        		
        		<opener>
            <dateline><date value="1916-12-15">Dec 15th [1916]</date></dateline>
            
            <salute>Dear Marcelle:</salute>
        		</opener>
        		
            <p>
            I was very pleased
            to hear from you to day.  Hope
            you received letter I sent
            you yesterday.
            </p><p>
            No, we won’t be 
            materially further from front
            at our new post, but I hope
            under a different army, for the
            orders we get now are wild.
            Two Frenchmen flying in rain this
            a.m. fired on each other.  I
            wish you had let me know
            before that you were not
            going before 2nd week in Jan.
            for I would have planned
            for a leave near the 1st.
            Now de Laage takes his then.
            </p><p>
            You’re really too
            sweet to send me a package
            for Xmas &mdash; but if you have
            already decided on it why
            just send it as you do
            
            <pb n="[p.2]"/>
            
            a letter.  Everything but
            large packages can go that
            way.  I’m sending you a
            petite chose that will do
            me more good than you &mdash; or 
            at least I hope so.
            </p><p>
            No, I shall be at front
            for Xmas &mdash; I think, and
            I’ll drink your health in
            the best we get that
            day.
            </p><p>
            Its too cold to write
            more, dear &mdash;
            </p>
        		
        		<closer>
            <salute>Good night</salute>
            
            <signed>Jim</signed>
        		</closer>
        		
            <!-- [With this letter is an envelope addressed to Mademoiselle Marcelle Guerin, 148 Bis Rue de Longchamp, XVI, Paris.] -->
            
            </div1>
        </body>
